<figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe2aca0ee-69a8-4085-bf4e-714e49383dc5_690x709.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/DfUr8aoDzha9agZ2If0mGpO2_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/kgzsmjGsdttwxw9gT201- 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Yga4h9i9afIBjZhzRvL8m-- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/5U1OcITMN67y7qO_I1SsdeyF- 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/bBxl8eozx92canarYq7nMfXf6vAOB_p7eV0_0lu47_M=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGZTJhY2EwZWUtNjlhOC00MDg1LWJmNGUtNzE0ZTQ5MzgzZGM1XzY5MHg3MDkuanBlZw==" width="458" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/O67mALdFH75etGEEjwtOrVsU_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/jn95fl6SsMsMNmeD7kFA-jjlsYse7tKxRtb7K-c2-iA=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGZTJhY2EwZWUtNjlhOC00MDg1LWJmNGUtNzE0ZTQ5MzgzZGM1XzY5MHg3MDkuanBlZw== 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/bBxl8eozx92canarYq7nMfXf6vAOB_p7eV0_0lu47_M=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGZTJhY2EwZWUtNjlhOC00MDg1LWJmNGUtNzE0ZTQ5MzgzZGM1XzY5MHg3MDkuanBlZw== 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>From <em>Vanitas</em> (1543) by Hans Holbein the Younger</figcaption></figure><p>This week, <em><a href="https://www.fantasy-magazine.com/fm/non-fiction/editorial-august-2023/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Fantasy </a></em><a href="https://www.fantasy-magazine.com/fm/non-fiction/editorial-august-2023/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">magazine announced it was shutting down</a> three years after it rebooted. <em>Fantasy </em>did great work in those years and their stories were regular SFF award contenders. Still, editors Christie Yant and Arley Sorg wrote “People will want to know why, of course, and the answer is the expected one: Unfortunately Fantasy never reached a point of paying for itself, and with the Kindle Periodicals mess it’s just not sustainable.” </p><p>The closing of a popular and professional SFF magazine is always a bummer. And it has a lot of people in the SFF world talking about the dire state of magazines and short stories. Literary magazines are always in a precarious state, and SFF mags in particularly are hurt by the new <a href="https://www.patreon.com/posts/genre-grapevine-80016042" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Kindle Periodical decision</a>. How did we get to this state, when a magazine surviving a few years is a miracle and even the top ones can’t fund themselves? </p><p>I’ve seen a lot of comments about how SFF magazines are too insular or don’t do enough to attract new readers. That only other writers read SFF magazines even though surely there’re many readers hungry for good short stories who aren’t served by the magazines. This may all be true. At the same time, it makes me reflect—<a href="https://countercraft.substack.com/p/a-long-post-about-short-stories-and" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">as I sometimes do here</a>—on the differences between genre magazines and quote unquote literary magazines. Because normally it’s the SFF magazines held up as doing things the right way. </p><p>By “right way,” I mean that SFF magazines always pay their authors and put real efforts into building subscriber bases. They reach outside of an audience of MFA-degree-holding writers and often have strong social media presences. This is a point of real (and deserved) pride in the SFF world. The lit mag world is more lax. While some lit mags pay even more than the best genre mags, it’s true that the vast majority pay little to nothing. Contributor copies mostly or if you’re lucky a $50 honorarium. Lit mags have also, I think, largely embraced not being financially viable and have accepted they will survive based on contest fees, non-profit grants, crowdfunding, and/or university sponsorship. (Or more unethically off submission fees.) As such, they spend less time trying to gain subscribers. </p><p>While the professionalism of SFF magazines is fantastic, especially when it comes to contracts and paying authors, the failure of <em>Fantasy </em>does show how the genre mags haven’t figured out how to sustain themselves on subscriptions either. There’s no genre of short fiction in a financially thriving state. SFF mags may not rely on university sponsorship and MFA student volunteer labor, but even the best of them depend on crowdfunding and such to survive. (Here I note that you <a href="https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/lynnemthomas/uncanny-magazine-year-10-a-decade-of-delightful-defiance" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">still have two days left to contribute to </a><em><a href="https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/lynnemthomas/uncanny-magazine-year-10-a-decade-of-delightful-defiance" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Uncanny Magazine</a></em><a href="https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/lynnemthomas/uncanny-magazine-year-10-a-decade-of-delightful-defiance" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">’s Kickstarter campaign</a>. They’re well worth your support and readership.) </p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4ab084a9-8771-4e09-a88b-0c8f5e1ad9a2_983x555.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/WoVkpJ6t5mJBfalZr5pW4XLI7qNm-CuNzKBvNmBtgS4=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNGFiMDg0YTktODc3MS00ZTA5LWE4OGItMGM4ZjVlMWFkOWEyXzk4M3g1NTUucG5n 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/tQIrfLM6cnN87B2u1b74Rskle3TWHoce-t-lNf_hOq0=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNGFiMDg0YTktODc3MS00ZTA5LWE4OGItMGM4ZjVlMWFkOWEyXzk4M3g1NTUucG5n" width="481" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/4V1lbNCVvFVaZHHYczysRLGGQzNAghGmN_FRyr1XTn4=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY0YWIwODRhOS04NzcxLTRlMDktYTg4Yi0wYzhmNWUxYWQ5YTJfOTgzeDU1NS5wbmc= 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/RT- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/tQIrfLM6cnN87B2u1b74Rskle3TWHoce-t-lNf_hOq0=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNGFiMDg0YTktODc3MS00ZTA5LWE4OGItMGM4ZjVlMWFkOWEyXzk4M3g1NTUucG5n 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a></figure><p>Ultimately, the problems of literary magazines in any genre go far beyond business models. The readers just aren’t there. And the readers who are there are less and less likely to pay. All the usual culprits are to blame: Too many competing entertainment options. Declining shelf space at bookstores. The internet making people expect free content. Etc. I’m not saying anything new, but is there anything new to say? </p><p>I do find the state of literary and SFF magazines sad. Reading literary magazines is how I discovered countless writers, and also where I honed my early work and gained the confidence to keep going. If you can afford it, subscribing is supporting writers. And, hey, you’ll probably find some great work you’d never have encountered otherwise. </p><p>I’ve seen people argue that literary magazines are antiquated and we should embrace just publishing our work ourselves, but I think we lose quite a lot when we lose literary magazines. For one, you lose a readership outside of your immediate network. Anyway, I’ve lamented this before: </p><p>And sure, maybe SFF magazines are too insular and maybe they could find some other readers with different stories or marketing. But I’m skeptical anything is going to return us to the subscriber readership of decades past to make lit mags be able to pay an editorial staff healthy salaries and also pay writers real money. What magazines do—crowdfund, grants, wealthy patrons, beg—is probably most of what they can do. It’s easy to say “do something different!” but harder to actually figure out what that is and make it work. </p><p>Still, as I post this on Substack I can’t help but wonder if newsletters offer a viable path for at least a few lit mags. There are lots of journalists who earn a living on platforms like Substack and more than a few SFF writers who earn legitimate income publishing stories on Patreon. (I don’t earn anywhere near a living off of my subscribers but I earn about as much as I’d get publishing these articles on literary sites that mostly pay 50 bucks a piece.) For whatever reason, a lot of readers are happier paying 5 bucks a month on these platforms than they are paying the equivalent of that for a magazine subscription. </p><p>It also seems to me that the SFF anthology market is doing quite well. To pick one example I’m excited about, I’ve seen lots of buzz about this forthcoming <a href="https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/676736/out-there-screaming-by-edited-by-jordan-peele/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Jordan Peele-edited horror anthology.</a>  There are readers who will pay 30 bucks for a <em>book</em> of stories that for whatever reason don’t care about paying 30 bucks for an <em>issue</em> of those same stories. Perhaps magazines need to shift towards more of an anthology mindset, with  a focus on special themed issues sold in bookstores? (Though plenty do that already…)</p><figure><a href="https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/676736/out-there-screaming-by-edited-by-jordan-peele/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ORvsXUrSQCELkTrrd7m2NLKFHiy_7kE7rI5BkFEClDQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY0ZmMyNGFiYS1iOTEyLTQ3N2MtODYyYi02ODE4NGI3YjFkMWFfMzA2eDQ1MC5qcGVn 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/RrO7t7FRFhLQwnoEOtse-QX_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/TvqZFhE3FkOfkrxZ5FOZ- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/sITzlU87xyCpoDnoFtwE5kVEv9PpDg_Iv7Pgb0sjA6Q=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNGZjMjRhYmEtYjkxMi00NzdjLTg2MmItNjgxODRiN2IxZDFhXzMwNng0NTAuanBlZw== 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Hob6IQZ1wE8uCoDgmIpzZR-W0A-" width="176" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/T- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/6T2kYiXCmPSHJONgxxNGbDx7z7RaxISfPG-5fVcN9uc=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY0ZmMyNGFiYS1iOTEyLTQ3N2MtODYyYi02ODE4NGI3YjFkMWFfMzA2eDQ1MC5qcGVn 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Hob6IQZ1wE8uCoDgmIpzZR-W0A- 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure><p>And while I wish literary mags paid as frequently of SFF magazines, the embrace (or acceptance) of their economic irrelevance has led to an artistically thriving literary magazine ecosystem. There hundreds of literary magazines in America that publish in countless styles, formats, and concepts. They might not have many readers and most not pay, but they’re out there publishing interesting work and fostering young writers. The SFF world is more professional but far more constrained. There are only a dozen or two SFF mags that people pay attention to. Only a handful seem to compete for Hugos and Nebulas. Perhaps the SFF world will at some point embrace the state of things and accept a little less professionalism or a little more artistic flourishing? </p><p>You don’t need to tell me this isn’t ideal or that it hurts poor writers to publish for free. That’s all true. But noting it doesn’t make subscriber dollars appear. </p><p>To end on a more positive note, I’d caution against reading too much into the state of short fiction overall. Short fiction isn’t dead. Or at least not anymore dead than it was a decade or two ago. There are far more literary magazine <em>readers</em> than there are <em>subscribers</em> in this online age. As I said, anthologies of short fiction often do well. Short stories are regularly optioned for film and TV. And in both SFF and literary fiction, short story collections seem to have made something of a comeback in recent years. But until something radical changes, literary magazines will stay largely a passion project. Financially precarious if artistically flourishing. </p><p>Counter Craft is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.</p><p><em>If you like this newsletter, <a href="https://countercraft.substack.com/subscribe" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">consider subscribing</a> or checking out my recent science fiction novel </em><a href="https://bookshop.org/books/the-body-scout/9780316628723" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">The Body Scout</a><em> that </em>The New York Times<em> called “Timeless and original…a wild ride, sad and funny, surreal and intelligent.”</em></p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F964e4e93-43d4-4e81-89d4-b7e2d5c3c1b1_443x675.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_UowVJU9mGV7c1xdn_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux." width="107" alt="" title="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/2ID0k1PNCQYuoKRgvUPhNJGGjBBEVBVhnkn- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ScRZZb7WK_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/-GDM6efIWBwE0-cuAWVERFo_4hAwC3t- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></pictur